About 20,000 were bussed in from Sydney and Melbourne, bringing with them an aggressive nationalism which they vented on pro-Tibet supporters. The sea of Chinese flags along the route of the flame, particularly at Reconciliation Place on the shores of Lake Burley Griffin, were a direct consequence of decisions taken by successive federal governments.
